149
00:21:16,670 --> 00:21:17,520
You don't like it, eh?

150
00:21:17,520 --> 00:21:20,530
I like it fine. They just don't feel the same way.

151
00:21:22,730 --> 00:21:24,050
I've prepared the master bedroom.

152
00:21:24,830 --> 00:21:27,520
No. My room will be fine.

153
00:21:27,520 --> 00:21:30,680
With all due respect, sir, Wayne Manor is your house.

154
00:21:30,700 --> 00:21:32,660
No, Alfred, it's my father's house.

155
00:21:32,960 --> 00:21:34,270
Your father is dead, Master Wayne.

156
00:21:34,270 --> 00:21:37,580
This place is a mausoleum. If I have my way, I'll pull the damn thing down brick by brick.

157
00:21:38,520 --> 00:21:42,300
This house, Master Wayne, has sheltered six generations of your family.

158
00:21:42,940 --> 00:21:45,180
Why do you give a damn, Alfred? It's not your family.

159
00:21:45,340 --> 00:21:54,000
I give a damn because a good man once made me responsible for what was most precious to him in our world.

160
00:21:57,540 --> 00:21:59,840
Miss Dawes has offered to drive you to the hearing.

161
00:22:01,170 --> 00:22:03,010
She probably hopes to talk you out of going.

162
00:22:03,330 --> 00:22:06,390
Should I just bury the past out there with my parents, Alfred?

163
00:22:06,870 --> 00:22:09,350
I wouldn't presume to tell you what to do with your past, sir.

164
00:22:10,190 --> 00:22:13,730
Just know that there are those of us who care about what you do with your future.

165
00:22:15,700 --> 00:22:16,840
Haven't given up on me yet?

166
00:22:17,900 --> 00:22:18,100
Never.

167
00:23:07,660 --> 00:23:10,450
Alfred still keeps the condensed milk on the top shelf.

168
00:23:12,220 --> 00:23:14,040
Hasn't he noticed you're tall enough to reach now?

169
00:23:14,440 --> 00:23:15,740
We'll have as thy heart, I guess.

170
00:23:15,980 --> 00:23:17,240
Never used to stop us anyway.

171
00:23:17,660 --> 00:23:19,180
No, it didn't. How's your mom?

172
00:23:20,900 --> 00:23:22,020
She misses this place.

173
00:23:24,760 --> 00:23:25,240
So do I.

174
00:23:26,740 --> 00:23:26,980
Yeah.

175
00:23:28,170 --> 00:23:30,470
But it's nothing without the people who made it what it was.

176
00:23:31,110 --> 00:23:31,990
Now there's only Alfred.

177
00:23:33,330 --> 00:23:33,710
And you?

178
00:23:34,470 --> 00:23:35,510
I'm not staying, Rachel.

179
00:23:35,610 --> 00:23:36,930
You're just back for the hearing.

180
00:23:41,330 --> 00:23:45,560
Bruce, I don't suppose there's any way to convince you not to come.

181
00:23:46,040 --> 00:23:51,610
Someone at this proceeding should stand for my parents.

182
00:23:52,610 --> 00:23:54,190
We all loved your parents, Bruce.

183
00:23:54,810 --> 00:23:56,350
What Chill did is unforgivable.

184
00:23:56,650 --> 00:23:57,930
Then why's your boss letting him go?

185
00:23:59,650 --> 00:24:02,120
In prison, he shared a cell with Carmine Falcone.

186
00:24:02,120 --> 00:24:06,610
He learned things, and he will testify in exchange for early parole.

187
00:24:06,770 --> 00:24:08,890
Rachel, this man killed my parents.

188
00:24:11,250 --> 00:24:15,450
I cannot let that pass, and I need you to understand that, please.

189
00:24:20,270 --> 00:24:23,090
The Depression hit working people like Mr. Chill hardest of all.

190
00:24:23,790 --> 00:24:27,910
His crime was appalling, yes, but it was motivated not by greed, but by desperation.

191
00:24:29,150 --> 00:24:32,630
And given the 14 years already served, as well as its extraordinary level of cooperation

192
00:24:32,890 --> 00:24:34,990
with one of this office's most important investigations,

193
00:24:35,870 --> 00:24:37,830
we strongly endorse his petition for early release.

194
00:24:40,130 --> 00:24:40,890
Mr. Chill?

195
00:24:48,570 --> 00:24:51,050
Not a day goes by that I don't wish I could take back what I did.

196
00:24:54,330 --> 00:24:55,170
I'm sure I was desperate.

197
00:24:55,490 --> 00:24:58,630
Like a lot of people back then, but they don't change what they did.

198
00:25:03,690 --> 00:25:07,830
I gather there's a member of the Wayne family here today.

199
00:25:08,590 --> 00:25:09,710
Has he got anything to say?

200
00:25:56,720 --> 00:25:57,820
We don't need to see this.

201
00:26:06,430 --> 00:26:10,130
The DA couldn't understand why Judge Faden insisted on making the hearing public.

202
00:26:10,770 --> 00:26:12,750
Falcone paid him off to get Chill out in the open.

203
00:26:13,090 --> 00:26:14,290
Maybe I should be thanking them.

204
00:26:14,690 --> 00:26:15,250
You don't mean that.

205
00:26:15,630 --> 00:26:16,550
What if I do, Rachel?

206
00:26:17,370 --> 00:26:18,710
My parents deserve justice.

207
00:26:19,350 --> 00:26:22,030
You're not talking about justice. You're talking about revenge.

208
00:26:22,370 --> 00:26:23,410
Sometimes they're the same.

209
00:26:23,750 --> 00:26:25,030
No, they're never the same, Bruce.

210
00:26:25,450 --> 00:26:26,550
Justice is about harmony.

211
00:26:26,650 --> 00:26:28,950
Revenge is about you making yourself feel better.

212
00:26:29,410 --> 00:26:30,810
That is why we have an impartial system.

213
00:26:31,110 --> 00:26:32,270
Well, your system is broken.

214
00:26:39,480 --> 00:26:40,740
You care about justice?

215
00:26:41,340 --> 00:26:42,720
Look beyond your own pain, Bruce.

216
00:26:43,080 --> 00:26:44,160
This city is rotting.

217
00:26:44,640 --> 00:26:47,240
They talk about the Depression as if it's history, and it's not.

218
00:26:47,600 --> 00:26:48,880
Things are worse than ever down here.

219
00:26:48,880 --> 00:26:51,660
Falcone floods our streets with crime and drugs,

220
00:26:51,660 --> 00:26:54,520
preying on the desperate, creating new Joe Chills every day.

221
00:26:54,520 --> 00:26:57,160
You know, Falcone may not have killed your parents, Bruce.

222
00:26:58,320 --> 00:27:00,240
He's destroying everything that they stood for.

223
00:27:05,280 --> 00:27:06,700
You want to thank him for that? Here you go.

224
00:27:10,150 --> 00:27:11,130
We all know where to find him.

225
00:27:11,590 --> 00:27:14,890
But as long as he keeps the bad people rich and the good people scared, no one will touch him.

226
00:27:15,350 --> 00:27:17,770
Good people like your parents will stand against injustice.

227
00:27:18,110 --> 00:27:18,810
They're gone.

228
00:27:19,710 --> 00:27:22,430
What chance does Gotham have when the good people do nothing?

229
00:27:24,580 --> 00:27:26,120
I'm not one of your good people, Rachel.

230
00:27:26,860 --> 00:27:27,460
What do you mean?

231
00:27:30,310 --> 00:27:31,990
All these years I wanted to kill him.

232
00:27:33,950 --> 00:27:34,790
Now I can't.

233
00:27:35,190 --> 00:27:53,140
I would be ashamed of you.

234
00:27:53,700 --> 00:28:38,990
You look in the tabloids, Mr. Wayne.

235
00:28:39,750 --> 00:28:40,970
No gun. I'm insulted.

236
00:28:44,620 --> 00:28:46,220
You could have just sent a thank you note.

237
00:28:46,460 --> 00:28:47,540
I didn't come here to thank you.

238
00:28:48,860 --> 00:28:51,330
I came here to show you that not everyone at Gotham's afraid of you.

239
00:28:51,330 --> 00:28:52,820
Only those who know me, kid.

240
00:28:53,580 --> 00:28:54,260
Look around you.

241
00:28:54,760 --> 00:29:00,230
You'll see two consulmen, a union official, a couple off-duty cops, and a judge.

242
00:29:01,050 --> 00:29:05,530
Now, I wouldn't have a second's hesitation in blowing your head off right here and right now in front of them.

243
00:29:05,530 --> 00:29:07,190
Now, that's power you can't buy.

244
00:29:09,290 --> 00:29:10,410
That's the power of fear.

245
00:29:10,990 --> 00:29:12,070
I'm not afraid of you.

246
00:29:12,570 --> 00:29:14,190
Because you think you got nothing to lose.

247
00:29:14,570 --> 00:29:15,490
But you haven't thought it through.

248
00:29:16,410 --> 00:29:19,150
You haven't thought about your lady friend down in the DA's office.

249
00:29:19,630 --> 00:29:21,290
You haven't thought about your old butler.

250
00:29:21,830 --> 00:29:22,030
Bang!

251
00:29:26,300 --> 00:29:30,200
People from your world have so much to lose.

252
00:29:31,320 --> 00:29:35,240
Now you think because your mommy and your daddy got shot,

253
00:29:35,860 --> 00:29:38,500
you know about the ugly side of life, but you don't.

254
00:29:38,880 --> 00:29:40,360
You've never tasted desperate.

255
00:29:41,260 --> 00:29:43,940
You're Bruce Wayne, the Prince of Gotham.

256
00:29:44,020 --> 00:29:46,640
you'd have to go a thousand miles to meet someone who didn't know your name.

257
00:29:46,780 --> 00:29:49,280
So don't come down here with your anger,

258
00:29:49,760 --> 00:29:51,520
trying to prove something to yourself.

259
00:29:52,080 --> 00:29:53,480
This is a world you'll never understand,

260
00:29:54,140 --> 00:29:57,330
and you always fear what you don't understand.

261
